---

🔴 Root Cause (Most Likely)

Exit code 126 in Podman usually means:

> ❌ Permission / SELinux / execution issue inside container



In mirror-registry setups, this is almost always one of these:

1. SELinux blocking container access


2. Wrong permissions on mounted directories


3. Missing execute permission inside container runtime


4. Podman / runc mismatch




---

✅ Step-by-Step Fix (Do this exactly)

1. Check real container error

Run this first — this gives the actual failure reason:

journalctl -u quay-app.service -n 100 -f

AND:

podman logs quay-app

👉 Paste output if still stuck.


---

2. Fix SELinux (VERY COMMON ISSUE)

Run:

setenforce 0

Then restart:

systemctl restart quay-app

👉 If it works → SELinux is the problem

Permanent fix:

setsebool -P container_manage_cgroup on
restorecon -Rv /root/quay-install


---

3. Fix permissions on volumes

Your mount paths:

/root/quay-install/quay-config

volumes: quay-storage, sqlite-storage


Run:

chmod -R 777 /root/quay-install

Then:

podman volume inspect quay-storage
podman volume inspect sqlite-storage

If needed recreate:

podman volume rm quay-storage sqlite-storage
podman volume create quay-storage
podman volume create sqlite-storage


---

4. Verify pod is running

podman pod ps
podman ps -a

If container keeps restarting:

podman inspect quay-app | grep -i error


---

5. Check image execution issue

Exit 126 can also mean binary issue. Try manual run:

podman run --rm registry.redhat.io/quay/quay-rhel8:v3.12.14 /bin/bash

If this fails → issue with container runtime / permissions.


---

6. Quick clean reinstall (if needed)

If things look messy, clean fully and reinstall:

systemctl stop quay-app quay-pod redis
podman rm -f quay-app
podman pod rm -f quay-pod
podman volume rm quay-storage sqlite-storage

rm -rf /root/quay-install
rm -rf ~/.quay

Then reinstall again.


